Introduction

Weâve gone over a preliminar look at the diamonds dataset, but now weâll be exploring the variables more in depth and at more than one at a time.

While we did have multiple variables shown on the same graph, we never really used any statistics to determine how much each variable affects the price and even if they affect each other instead of the final price.

Initial Looks and Refresher

We already had a good look at the data. Some of the variables we didnât look at were the x, y, and z.

A quick summary of the variables.

Variable Detail
price price in USD (326-18,823)
carat weight (0.2 - 5.01)
cut quality of cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal)
color J (worst) to D (best)
clarity how clear diamond is (I1 (worst), SI1, SI2, VS1, VS2, VVS1, VVS2, IF (best))
x length in mm (0 - 10.74)
y width in mm (0 - 58.9)
z depth in mm (0 - 31.8)
depth total depth percentage = z / mean(x, y) (43 - 79)
table width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43 - 95)

X,Y,Z and Everything on the Table

Letâs put the x, y, and z variables to a test of their correlation to price. Recall - a pearson corr factor of 0 means there is no linear relationship between the two, whereas a value of 1 means there is a strong linear correlation.

Correlation of :

  • x and price: 0.88
  • y and price: 0.87
  • z and price: 0.86
x_range <- range(df$depth)
x_lab <- seq(x_range[1], x_range[2], 2)
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = depth, y = price)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 1/50) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = x_lab,
                       labels = x_lab)

Looking at the graph above, we can get a better understanding of the depth of diamonds, and what the price looks like.

All diamonds seem to be confined to a depth of 59 and 64. But would we consider this a correlation? What does Pearson say?

Pearson correlation coefficient: -0.01 Survey saysâ¦ Not any correlation. A correlation coefficient close to 0 (within one hundredth) indicates that there is weak (if any) correlation. We probably couldâve concluded that from the graph, but good to see a number that says otherwise too.

V = nRT/P for Diamonds

Since x,y, and z make up the variables for width, height, and depth, it follows that we should be able to estimate a volume from those values. Itâs a very rough estimate, but should give us some insight into those 3 factors as a whole, but not which one has more influence.

## Making a new variable with mutate

df <- df %>% mutate(volume = x*y*z)

## And plotting with gg

ggplot(df, aes(x = volume, y = price)) +
  geom_point()

Look at that. The price seems to trend nicely with the volume variable. There are some obvious outliers that are throwing the scale off, so instead of just throwing them out, we should probably look at them and figure out why they donât fit the trend.

My initial thought is if the volume is so outrageously high, why doesnât the price follow that as well? A high volume would indicate a large diamond, which seems to imply a large price. Perhaps someone moved a decimal place over to where it shouldnât have been? I suppose thatâs what EDA is all about.

Just for fun, weâll stack the histogram charts; however, I did not find an easy solution to do this, so ended up having to pull out the values from the original dataframe and putting them into a new one as a single âvolumeâ variable.

# Each of the variables for volume with its variable ID
x_val <- df %>% select(x) %>% mutate(var = "x")
y_val <- df %>% select(y) %>% mutate(var = "y")
z_val <- df %>% select(z) %>% mutate(var = "z")

# Renaming so we can combine them properly
names(x_val) <- names(y_val) <- names(z_val) <- c("val", "var")

# And now combine to one data frame
vol_full <- rbind.data.frame(x_val, y_val, z_val, stringsAsFactors = F)

# Tidy up our workspace first
rm(x_val, y_val, z_val)

# Now we plot
cbPalette <- c("#1b85b8", "#5a5255", "#c3cb71")
ggplot(vol_full, aes(x = val, fill = var)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, alpha = 0.6) + 
  coord_trans(y = "sqrt") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = cbPalette)

That was not totally necessary, but it helps to understand and show the different outliers. I think the other graph did a better job of showing the varying distributions between the volume dimensions. Interesting, nonetheless to see the different distributions on the same scale.

Impact of Volume

If we are to exclude the diamonds with a volume of 0, we can get a better idea for the correlation to price.

We are also going to exclude any diamond with a volume greater than 800, similar to what was shown above for the outliers.

Based on that, the correlation between price and volume is now 0.92.

Plotting this should give us a better idea of what that correlation factor is, as being that close to 1, there is a reason to explore this further.

df.vtp <- subset(df, volume > 0 & volume < 800)

ggplot(df.vtp, aes(volume, price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/5) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm') +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 20000))
## Warning: Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_smooth).

Adding a smoothed linear model to the data gives us a good visual representation of the trend; however, in looking at the graph, it seems that a linear model is not the best method. While the linear model does fit reasonably well, especially with the 0.92 factor, a non-linear may get us closer for all ranges of volume - perhaps a parabolic fit?

Mean Price by Clarity

Next weâll delve into looking at the mean price by clarity. To begin weâll create a new dataframe that is a summary of the diamonds data set, but is focusing on clarity.

diamondsByClarity <- df %>% 
  group_by(clarity) %>% 
  summarise(mean_price = mean(price),
            median_price = median(price),
            min_price = min(price),
            max_price = max(price),
            n = n())

Weâll also create a data frame that goes through the same summaries, but for color instead of clarity.

diamondsByColor <- df %>% 
  group_by(color) %>% 
  summarise(mean_price = mean(price),
            median_price = median(price),
            min_price = min(price),
            max_price = max(price),
            n = n())

We can compare the two variables by plotting color and clarity in tandem to get an idea of how they each effect price.

diamonds_mp_by_clarity <- diamondsByClarity %>% select(clarity, mean_price)
diamonds_mp_by_color <- diamondsByColor %>% select(color, mean_price) %>% arrange(desc(color))

# Rearrange order for color to be lowest to greatest
diamonds_mp_by_color$color <- with(diamonds_mp_by_color, factor(color, levels = rev(levels(color))))

p1 <- ggplot(diamonds_mp_by_clarity, aes(x = clarity, y = mean_price)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', fill = "#5e3c58") +
  labs(y = "Mean Price") +
  ggtitle("Mean Price by Clarity") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 5000, 1000), limits = c(0, 5500))

p2 <- ggplot(diamonds_mp_by_color, aes(x = color, y = mean_price)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', fill = "#fb2e01") +
  labs(y = "") +
  ggtitle("Mean Price by Color") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 5000, 1000), limits = c(0, 5500))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

By arranging these side by side and ordered from least (left) to greatest (right) of clarity and color, the mean price continues to trend lower. While the clarity field seems to be a gradual trend towards cheaper mean price, the color of the diamond has greater price drops between colors.

This may indicate that color is more of a driving factor as it seems to vary more over price.

Conlcusion

This is the end of the segment that udacity asked for analysis. Thereâs definitely more work to be done though as the mean price begs a deeper dive into how the cut, clarity, and color affect the price, but also why the decrease as the diamondâs respective quality increases.

One of the bigger pieces to take away from this piece is how greatly, and well, price is affected by volume. Putting together a regression model and put some values to all the variables should be the next step in this process.
